\b \cf2 ##### Margaret Mead\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl440\sa360

\b0\fs36 \cf2 Margaret mead under scrutiny\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl480\sa240

\i\fs24 \cf2 Coming of Age in Samoa
\i0 \'a0came under intense scrutiny after a half-century as an anthropological classic. In books published in 1983 and 1998, Derek Freeman charged that Mead\'92s work suffered from too many biasing preconceptions, too much gullibility, and too little data. He went so far as to re-interview some of the same individuals, now at the other end of their lives, and reported an important recantation. Though Mead had many defenders, the damage to her reputation sent a message to ambitious young anthropologists that accurate and thorough observation is the bedrock upon which even the cleverest accounts must stand. That is, they must become skilled ethnographers.*\
*Ethnographers seek to describe and understand each culture from its own perspective, using techniques that emphasize naturalistic settings, the meaning and context of activities and practices, and qualitative analysis. Such techniques as participant observation and in-depth interviews yield detailed records (written field-notes, audio and video recordings, etc.) that must be distilled and interpreted to obtain a usable account of the culture or some aspect of the culture. Today these techniques are increasingly being applied to the study of microcultures within the ethnologist\'92s own culture. For example, Bonnie Nardi moved from studying the culture of Samoa as an outsider to studying corporate microcultures in Silicon Valley as more of an insider. She informally discusses her work at\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://argus-acia.com/people/current_profile.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 http://argus-acia.com/people/current_profile.html}}.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl480\sa240

