\f1\b\fs32 \cf5 \strokec5 Chomsky
\f3 \'92
\f1 s theory\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl480\sa240

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 The earliest versions of generative grammar emphasized the idea (adapted from Chomsky\'92s mentor, Zellig Harris) that a sentence should be viewed as the product of a series of transformations. The following sequence leaves out Chomsky\'92s linguistic symbols but gets across the general idea:\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\qc
\cf2 John will read what? BASE QUESTION (atypical word order for a question)\uc0\u8232 What John will read? PREPOSING TRANSFORMATION: moves wh-word (
\i what
\i0 ) to the front.\'a0\uc0\u8232 What will John read? TRANSPOSING TRANSFORMATION: reverses the subject (
\i John
\i0 ) and the auxiliary verb (
\i will
\i0 ).\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl480\sa240
\cf2 The final form in the sequence is what an adult would typically say. The transformations and the intermediate form are not directly observed, but Chomsky claimed that they can be inferred and are part of the speaker\'92s linguistic competence.\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl960\sa320

\f1\b\fs32 \cf5 \strokec5 Brown
\f3 \'92
\f1 s use of Chomsky
\f3 \'92
\f1 s theory to analyze the observation\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl480\sa240

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 Brown and his colleagues suggested that the child was in the process of acquiring transformations, and at this point (about 3 years of age) had acquired preposing but not transposing. As a result, the \'93hypothetical intermediate\'94 became an actual, observed form. Not only did this give a neat explanation of what the child said, but in the other direction it lent support to Chomsky\'92s theory.\
\pard\intbl\itap1\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\qc
